        <h2 id="examples">Real link in bio examples by goal</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — ecommerce brand</h3>
        <p>A clothing brand's link in bio page has four buttons: "Shop new arrivals", "Current sale — 30% off", "Size guide", and "Our Instagram page". The sale button moves to the top whenever a discount is live and gets removed after the promotion ends. Click data shows the sale button gets 68% of all taps during promotion windows — validating the priority ranking.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — content creator</h3>
        <p>A fitness creator with 180,000 Instagram followers uses their bio page to route different audience segments. Buttons include: "Free 7-day workout plan" (email capture), "YouTube channel", "Coaching enquiry form", and "Merch store". The free plan button drives 250-300 email subscribers per week from bio traffic alone.</p>

        <h3>Example 3 — B2B SaaS company</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company uses a self-hosted link in bio page at <code>theirdomain.com/links/</code> to maintain SEO ownership. Buttons include the product demo, latest case study, and a job listings page. Because it is on their own domain, clicks feed into their GA4 data without a third-party tool intermediary.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Link in bio tool vs direct website link — which to use?</h2>
        <p>Not every account needs a link in bio tool. The choice depends on how many destinations you want to surface and how often they change.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use a link in bio tool when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You have 3+ destinations to promote simultaneously</li>
              <li>Your top priority link changes frequently (campaigns, launches)</li>
              <li>You want per-link click analytics</li>
              <li>You want to embed an email capture form</li>
              <li>You run a creator account with products, merch, and content</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use a direct website link when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Your single website homepage covers all destinations via navigation</li>
              <li>You have one primary CTA (e.g. book a call)</li>
              <li>SEO attribution is critical and you cannot self-host the bio page</li>
              <li>Your audience is highly brand-aware and knows where to go</li>
              <li>You want to avoid adding another tool to your stack</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">5 best practices for an effective link in bio page</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Lead with your highest-value destination.</strong> Most people only tap the first button. Put your most important CTA — free trial, lead magnet, or current offer — at the top, not buried in position 5.</li>
          <li><strong>Use action-oriented button labels.</strong> "Download free guide" converts better than "Blog". "Book a demo" converts better than "Website". Tell users what they are going to get, not where they are going.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep it to 5-7 buttons maximum.</strong> More options cause decision paralysis. Audit quarterly and remove any destination that receives under 2% of clicks. Less is almost always more on a link in bio page.</li>
          <li><strong>Update it with every major content push.</strong> If you post about a new YouTube video or podcast episode, add it to your bio page for the week. Timely linking captures the traffic while it is warm.</li>
          <li><strong>Self-host if SEO matters to your brand.</strong> A page at <code>yourdomain.com/links/</code> keeps backlink equity and GA4 attribution in your own ecosystem. Many website builders (Webflow, Squarespace, WordPress) make this easy with a simple links page template.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — set it and forget it</div>
          <p>The most common link in bio error is setting up the page during an account launch and never revisiting it. Stale pages with dead links, expired promotions, or outdated products signal to followers that the brand does not maintain its presence. Block 15 minutes monthly to audit every button and remove anything that no longer serves your audience.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common link in bio tool mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Too many buttons:</strong> A page with 15 links overwhelms visitors. Prioritise ruthlessly — if you cannot explain why a link is there in one sentence, cut it.</li>
          <li><strong>Generic button labels:</strong> "Click here" or "Shop" give no information about what the user gets. Specificity drives clicks.</li>
          <li><strong>No email capture:</strong> A link in bio page is ideal real estate for a newsletter opt-in. If you have one, embed it — it converts better than sending followers to a standalone form page.</li>
          <li><strong>Third-party branding when you want SEO:</strong> Linktree's free plan shows their branding and lives on their domain. If organic search visibility matters, use a self-hosted page on your own domain.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring analytics:</strong> Every major link in bio tool shows per-link click data. Ignoring it means you cannot learn which offers and destinations your audience actually cares about.</li>
        </ul>

